a binomial distribution?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The probability changes with each successive child","Fixed number of trials with two possible outcomes per trial","The outcomes are dependent on previous results","The number of trials can vary between families","The probability must equal 25%"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA binomial distribution is a fundamental probability distribution that describes the number of successes in a fixed number of independent trials, where each trial has exactly two possible outcomes. It is important in medical research for analyzing dichotomous outcomes like treatment success/failure or presence/absence of disease traits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario represents a binomial distribution because it has a \u003Cstrong\u003Efixed number of trials with two possible outcomes per trial\u003C/strong\u003E. The key characteristics that make this a binomial distribution are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFixed number of trials (four children)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEach trial (child) has exactly two possible outcomes (expresses trait or not)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe probability remains constant (25% for each child)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe trials are independent (outcome for one child doesn\u0027t affect others)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe probability changes with each successive child\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ethe outcomes are dependent on previous results \u003C/strong\u003E- In a binomial distribution, probability must remain constant\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe number of trials can vary between families\u003C/strong\u003E - A binomial distribution requires a fixed number of trials\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe probability must equal 25% \u003C/strong\u003E - The actual probability value doesn\u0027t matter, as long as it\u0027s constant\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these characteristics helps identify when to apply binomial probability calculations in research and statistical analysis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The binomial distribution models the probability of a specific number of successes in a fixed number of independent trials.","The binomial distribution requires each trial to have only two possible outcomes with a constant probability.","The mean of a binomial distribution equals the number of trials multiplied by the probability of success."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60314"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18443"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60314"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-27T13:17:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-27T13:20:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11161"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74809"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"se